  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.vocab', 'ELA.4.V.1', '"Her smile was as bright as the sun." is an example of:', '["simile","personification","hyperbole","metaphor"]', 0, 'It compares using "like"/"as" — a simile.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.vocab', 'ELA.4.V.1', '"He was as busy as a bee." is an example of:', '["personification","simile","metaphor","hyperbole"]', 1, 'It compares using "like"/"as" — a simile.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.vocab', 'ELA.4.V.1', '"Time is a thief." is an example of:', '["metaphor","personification","simile","hyperbole"]', 0, 'It calls one thing another — a metaphor.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.vocab', 'ELA.4.V.1', '"The sun smiled down on us." is an example of:', '["simile","metaphor","personification","hyperbole"]', 2, 'It gives human traits to a non-human thing — personification.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.vocab', 'ELA.4.V.1', '"The snow was a soft white blanket." is an example of:', '["simile","metaphor","hyperbole","personification"]', 1, 'It calls one thing another — a metaphor.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.vocab', 'ELA.4.V.1', '"The thunder grumbled in the distance." is an example of:', '["personification","metaphor","hyperbole","simile"]', 0, 'It gives human traits to a non-human thing — personification.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.vocab', 'ELA.4.V.1', '"The flowers danced in the breeze." is an example of:', '["hyperbole","metaphor","simile","personification"]', 3, 'It gives human traits to a non-human thing — personification.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.vocab', 'ELA.4.V.1', '"The wind whispered through the trees." is an example of:', '["metaphor","personification","hyperbole","simile"]', 1, 'It gives human traits to a non-human thing — personification.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.vocab', 'ELA.4.V.1', '"As quiet as a mouse." is an example of:', '["hyperbole","simile","metaphor","personification"]', 1, 'It compares using "like"/"as" — a simile.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.vocab', 'ELA.4.V.1', '"The classroom was a zoo." is an example of:', '["metaphor","simile","personification","hyperbole"]', 0, 'It calls one thing another — a metaphor.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.vocab', 'ELA.4.V.1', '"She ran like the wind." is an example of:', '["metaphor","personification","simile","hyperbole"]', 2, 'It compares using "like"/"as" — a simile.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.vocab', 'ELA.4.V.1', '"The stars were diamonds in the sky." is an example of:', '["simile","metaphor","personification","hyperbole"]', 1, 'It calls one thing another — a metaphor.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.theme', 'ELA.4.R.1', 'Read: "Even though the puzzle was hard, Jo kept trying. At last, the final piece clicked into place." What is the theme (lesson)?', '["Never give up","Winning is easy","Puzzles are boring","Always ask for help"]', 0, 'Jo kept trying until she finished — the lesson is to never give up.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 3, '4.purpose', 'ELA.4.R.2', 'A writer lists reasons we should recycle and asks readers to start today. The author''s main purpose is to:', '["tell a joke","persuade","confuse","entertain"]', 1, 'Writing to convince the reader to do something is persuading.', 15),
  ('reading', '4', 2, '4.vocab', 'ELA.4.V.1', 'Read: "The fragile vase shattered the moment it slipped." The word "fragile" means:', '["colorful","strong","heavy","easily broken"]', 3, '"Fragile" means delicate and easily broken.', 15),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'For a bulb to light in a simple circuit, the path must be ___.', '["painted","broken","complete","wet"]', 2, 'Electricity needs a complete (closed) path to flow.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'What part stores the energy that makes a circuit work?', '["The wire alone","The switch alone","The air","The battery"]', 3, 'The battery supplies the energy for the circuit.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'What part can open or close a circuit to turn it on or off?', '["A magnet","A battery","A bulb","A switch"]', 3, 'A switch opens or closes the circuit.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Materials that let electricity flow through them are called ___.', '["conductors","magnets","shadows","insulators"]', 0, 'Conductors, like metal, let electricity flow.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Which is a good conductor of electricity?', '["Metal wire","Plastic","Dry wood","Rubber"]', 0, 'Metals are good conductors of electricity.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'If a wire in the circuit is broken, the bulb will ___.', '["make sound","change color","shine brighter","not light"]', 3, 'A broken path stops the electricity, so the bulb goes out.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'Heat naturally moves from a ___ object to a ___ object.', '["hotter object to a cooler one","in a circle forever","cooler object to a hotter one","to no object"]', 0, 'Heat flows from hot to cold.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'The sun''s energy travels to Earth as ___.', '["light and heat","electricity in wires","sound","wind"]', 0, 'The sun sends energy to Earth as light and heat.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'A moving object has ___ energy.', '["motion (kinetic)","frozen","sound only","no"]', 0, 'Anything moving has energy of motion.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'Plants change the sun''s light energy into ___.', '["sound energy","electricity","wind","stored food energy"]', 3, 'Plants store the sun''s energy as food (sugar).', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'When you turn on a lamp, electrical energy changes into ___.', '["light and heat","rain","only sound","wind"]', 0, 'A lamp turns electrical energy into light (and some heat).', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'Energy can change from one form to ___.', '["only sound","nothing","another","only light"]', 2, 'Energy can change forms, like electrical to light.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'The usual weather in a place over many years is called its ___.', '["a forecast","a single storm","climate","a season only"]', 2, 'Climate is the typical weather over a long time.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'Weather is what is happening ___.', '["right now","only at night","over 100 years","only in winter"]', 0, 'Weather is the conditions happening now or today.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'A place near the equator usually has a ___ climate.', '["freezing","dark","warm","snowy all year"]', 2, 'Places near the equator get strong sunlight and stay warm.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'Scientists who study the weather are called ___.', '["geologists","meteorologists","astronauts","zookeepers"]', 1, 'Meteorologists study and predict the weather.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'A tool that measures how much rain falls is a ___.', '["compass","thermometer","rain gauge","ruler for length"]', 2, 'A rain gauge collects and measures rainfall.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'Which sentence describes climate, not today''s weather?', '["It is raining right now.","The wind is strong today.","It is usually hot and dry here.","It is cloudy this afternoon."]', 2, 'Climate is the usual pattern; the others describe today.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'The moon seems to change shape because of how ___ lights it.', '["the Earth","a streetlamp","the sun","the stars"]', 2, 'We see the part of the moon lit by the sun, which changes.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'About how long does it take the moon to go through all its phases?', '["About a month","One day","One year","One hour"]', 0, 'The moon''s phases repeat about every 29–30 days.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'When we cannot see the lit moon at all, it is called a ___ moon.', '["full","new","blue","half"]', 1, 'At a new moon, the lit side faces away from us.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'When the whole lit side faces us, it is a ___ moon.', '["thin crescent","full","new","broken"]', 1, 'A full moon is when we see the entire lit side.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'The moon does not make its own light; it ___ the sun''s light.', '["blocks","creates","reflects","swallows"]', 2, 'The moon shines by reflecting sunlight.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'The moon moves around (orbits) the ___.', '["stars","Earth","Sun directly","Mars"]', 1, 'The moon orbits the Earth.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A polar bear''s thick fur is an adaptation that helps it stay ___.', '["cool in the desert","warm","fast in water only","invisible"]', 1, 'Thick fur keeps the polar bear warm in the cold.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A cactus stores ___ to survive in the dry desert.', '["rocks","sunlight in a box","sand","water"]', 3, 'A cactus stores water to live where it rarely rains.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'The shape of a bird''s beak helps it ___.', '["sing songs only","eat its kind of food","fly only","see at night"]', 1, 'Beak shapes are adapted to the foods birds eat.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'An adaptation is a feature that helps a living thing ___.', '["do homework","survive","get taller forever","stop eating"]', 1, 'Adaptations help living things survive in their habitat.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A fish has gills that let it ___.', '["breathe in water","sleep standing","walk on land","fly"]', 0, 'Gills let fish take oxygen from water.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A chameleon can change color to ___.', '["freeze water","make light","get taller","hide from danger"]', 3, 'Changing color helps a chameleon blend in (camouflage).', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'For a bulb to light up, the electric circuit must be ___.', '["broken","wet","upside down","complete"]', 3, 'Electricity needs a complete, unbroken path.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Which material lets electricity flow through it easily?', '["Metal wire","Plastic","Rubber","Dry wood"]', 0, 'Metals are good conductors of electricity.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'Heat always moves from a ___ object to a cooler one.', '["heavier","warmer","lighter","cooler"]', 1, 'Heat flows from hot to cold.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'The usual weather pattern of a place over many years is its ___.', '["forecast","temperature today","climate","season"]', 2, 'Climate is the long-term pattern; weather is day to day.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'About how long does the moon take to go through all its phases?', '["About one year","About one month","About one day","About one week"]', 1, 'The moon cycles through its phases roughly every month.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A polar bear''s thick fur is an adaptation that helps it survive the ___.', '["cold","heat","dark only","rain only"]', 0, 'Thick fur keeps the polar bear warm in the cold.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A bird that flies south for the winter to find food and warmth is doing something called', '["camouflage","migration","hibernation","photosynthesis"]', 1, 'Migration is when animals travel to a new place to survive seasonal changes.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'Sharp claws on a hawk are mainly an adaptation that helps it', '["breathe underwater","grab and hold its prey","blend into trees","stay warm in winter"]', 1, 'A hawk''s sharp claws grip animals it catches for food.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'Some desert animals are active only at night and rest during the hot day. This behavior helps them', '["grow taller quickly","change their color","make their own food","avoid the daytime heat"]', 3, 'Being active at night lets desert animals escape the strong daytime heat.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A seal''s thick layer of fat, called blubber, is an adaptation that helps it', '["stay warm in icy water","change its color","breathe under the sand","run fast on land"]', 0, 'Blubber traps heat and keeps the seal warm in very cold water.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A penguin''s smooth, packed feathers help it by', '["letting it fly very high","keeping its body warm and dry in cold water","making it taller","helping it dig burrows"]', 1, 'The tight feathers keep cold water out and trap warmth near the penguin''s body.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Materials that do NOT let electricity flow through them easily are called', '["batteries","insulators","conductors","magnets"]', 1, 'Insulators block the flow of electricity instead of letting it pass.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'The thin wire inside a light bulb that glows when electricity flows through it is called the', '["socket","switch","filament","battery"]', 2, 'The filament is the thin wire that heats up and glows to make light.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'What happens to the bulb when you open the switch in a working circuit?', '["the bulb gets brighter","the bulb turns off","the bulb changes color","the bulb gets bigger"]', 1, 'Opening the switch breaks the path, so electricity stops and the bulb goes off.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'A buzzer in a circuit changes electrical energy into', '["cold air","light only","sand","sound energy"]', 3, 'A buzzer uses electricity to make sound energy.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'A switch in a circuit works by', '["making its own light","storing all the energy","cooling the battery","opening or closing the path for electricity"]', 3, 'A switch opens the path to stop the flow or closes it to let electricity move.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'When you rub your hands together quickly, they get warm. This shows that motion can change into', '["water","light energy","sound only","heat energy"]', 3, 'Rubbing makes friction, which changes motion energy into heat.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'When a guitar string is plucked and vibrates, it makes', '["heat that cooks food","electricity","light energy","sound energy"]', 3, 'The vibrating string makes sound energy that we hear.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'Heat from a campfire can warm your face from across the fire. This way of moving heat is called', '["radiation","drinking","writing","floating"]', 0, 'Radiation is heat that travels through the air or space without touching.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'When a battery is used in a remote control car, the battery''s stored energy mostly becomes', '["ocean waves","light from the sun","motion energy","food energy"]', 2, 'The battery''s stored energy changes into motion that moves the car.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'A bicycle dynamo light glows when you pedal. The energy of your moving legs is changed into', '["food energy","ice","electrical energy","sand"]', 2, 'Pedaling motion is turned into electrical energy that lights the bulb.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'Earth''s daytime and nighttime are caused by', '["clouds covering the sun","Earth spinning on its axis","the sun turning off","the moon hiding the sun"]', 1, 'As Earth spins, one side faces the sun for day and the other faces away for night.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'The moon takes about one month to', '["spin around the sun","orbit once around Earth","grow larger","cool down"]', 1, 'The moon travels all the way around Earth in about a month.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'As the moon goes from a full moon back toward a new moon, the lit part we see is', '["getting bigger each night","staying the same","turning red","getting smaller each night"]', 3, 'After a full moon, the lit part we see shrinks a little each night.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'The pull of the moon''s gravity on Earth''s oceans mainly helps cause', '["the rising and falling of ocean tides","thunderstorms","rainbows","the four seasons"]', 0, 'The moon''s gravity tugs on the ocean water, creating high and low tides.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'Why does the moon look bigger than the stars at night?', '["it is brighter than the sun","it grows at night","it is much closer to Earth than the stars","it is the largest object in space"]', 2, 'The moon looks big because it is far nearer to Earth than the distant stars.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'A tool used to measure the temperature of the air is a', '["clock","scale","ruler","thermometer"]', 3, 'A thermometer measures how hot or cold the air is.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'When water vapor cools high in the sky and turns into tiny droplets that form clouds, this is called', '["condensation","freezing","melting","evaporation"]', 0, 'Condensation is when water vapor cools and turns back into liquid droplets.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'A spinning column of air that reaches down from a storm cloud to the ground is a', '["cloud bank","rainbow","tornado","sea breeze"]', 2, 'A tornado is a fast-spinning column of air that touches the ground.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'Cold places far from the equator, near the North and South Poles, usually have a climate that is', '["never windy","always rainy and warm","very hot","very cold"]', 3, 'Areas near the poles get little direct sunlight, so their climate is very cold.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'Looking at past weather records helps people', '["change today''s weather","make the sun rise earlier","stop hurricanes from forming","learn the usual climate of a place"]', 3, 'Records collected over many years show a place''s usual climate.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A bear sleeps deeply through the cold winter and lives off stored body fat. This behavior is called', '["hibernation","molting","blooming","migration"]', 0, 'Hibernation is a long winter sleep that helps animals survive when food is scarce.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A jackrabbit''s very large ears help it', '["release heat to stay cool","dig holes in the sand","store water for the dry season","glide between trees"]', 0, 'Heat leaves the jackrabbit''s body through its big thin ears, cooling it in the hot desert.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A giraffe''s long neck is an adaptation that helps it', '["fly over the grassland","swim across deep rivers","reach leaves high in tall trees","dig for water underground"]', 2, 'The long neck lets the giraffe eat leaves that shorter animals cannot reach.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A turtle''s hard shell is mostly an adaptation for', '["glowing in the dark","flying through the air","protection from predators","making its own food"]', 2, 'The hard shell shields the turtle''s soft body from animals that attack it.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'Some trees in cold places drop all their leaves before winter. This helps the tree by', '["making more sunlight","scaring away deer","saving water and energy during winter","growing new roots faster"]', 2, 'Dropping leaves helps the tree save water and energy when it is cold and dry.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Which material is the best insulator that keeps electricity from flowing?', '["iron","gold","copper","rubber"]', 3, 'Rubber is an insulator, so electricity does not flow through it easily.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Electricity flowing around a circuit is called an electric', '["echo","shadow","current","cloud"]', 2, 'An electric current is the flow of electricity through the circuit.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Electricity needs a complete loop to flow. This loop is called a', '["circuit","magnet","cloud","shadow"]', 0, 'A circuit is the complete loop that electricity travels around.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'If two parts of a circuit are not touching where they should, the circuit is', '["brighter than before","faster than before","cooler and safer","broken, so it will not work"]', 3, 'A gap breaks the loop, so electricity cannot flow and the circuit does not work.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Which is the best example of a conductor used in everyday wires?', '["cloth","wood","copper","glass"]', 2, 'Copper is a metal that conducts electricity very well, so it is used in wires.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'A metal spoon left in a bowl of hot soup gets warm. Heat moves through the solid spoon by', '["wind","gravity","conduction","sunlight"]', 2, 'Conduction is heat moving through a solid when its parts touch.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'In a food chain, a rabbit gets its energy by', '["drinking only water","making its own light","eating plants","using a battery"]', 2, 'The rabbit takes in energy that the plants first stored from the sun.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'When you slide down a slide, the energy you had at the top changes mostly into energy of', '["light","sound only","motion","electricity"]', 2, 'The stored energy from being high up changes into motion as you slide down.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'A pot of water boils on a stove because heat is moving from the', '["light into the ground","cool water into the stove","air into the moon","hot stove into the cooler water"]', 3, 'Heat always moves from the hotter stove to the cooler water.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'Warm air rising and cooler air sinking moves heat through the air. This is called', '["convection","reading","melting only","spinning"]', 0, 'Convection is heat carried by moving warm and cool air or water.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'The round dents on the moon''s surface, made by space rocks crashing into it, are called', '["craters","forests","oceans","clouds"]', 0, 'Craters are bowl-shaped holes made when space rocks hit the moon.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'Compared with Earth, the moon is', '["much smaller","made of water","exactly the same size","much larger"]', 0, 'The moon is a smaller body that orbits the much larger Earth.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'The phases of the moon happen because of', '["the moon getting hotter","the moon changing its real shape","clouds covering parts of the moon","how much of the sunlit moon we can see from Earth"]', 3, 'As the moon orbits, we see different amounts of its sunlit side, making phases.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'A new moon is hard to see in the sky because', '["it is hiding behind clouds","its lit side is facing away from Earth","it has turned off its light","it is too far to exist"]', 1, 'During a new moon, the sunlit side faces away from us, so we see almost nothing.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'Each night during one part of the cycle, the moon''s lit shape grows a little bigger. We say the moon is', '["spinning","setting","waxing","waning"]', 2, 'Waxing means the lit part of the moon we see is growing larger each night.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'A tool that shows the direction the wind is blowing from is a', '["rain gauge","thermometer","clock","wind vane"]', 3, 'A wind vane points to show which way the wind is coming from.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'Rain, snow, sleet, and hail that fall from clouds are all kinds of', '["wind","precipitation","sunlight","evaporation"]', 1, 'Precipitation is any form of water that falls from clouds to the ground.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'Florida is known for getting heavy afternoon thunderstorms most often during which season?', '["winter","early spring","late fall","summer"]', 3, 'Florida''s warm, humid summers bring frequent afternoon thunderstorms.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'The amount of water vapor in the air is called', '["temperature","sunlight","wind speed","humidity"]', 3, 'Humidity tells how much water vapor is in the air.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'Dark, thick clouds that often bring rain are called', '["sunbeams","fair-weather clouds","nimbus clouds","clear skies"]', 2, 'Nimbus clouds are the dark, heavy clouds that usually bring rain.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A green grasshopper sitting on green leaves is hard to see. This kind of hiding by blending in is called', '["pollination","camouflage","hibernation","migration"]', 1, 'Camouflage lets an animal blend with its surroundings so it is harder to spot.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A skunk sprays a bad smell when scared. This is an adaptation that helps it', '["find its food at night","stay warm in the cold","build a strong nest","defend itself from enemies"]', 3, 'The bad smell scares away animals that might try to eat the skunk.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A frog has a long sticky tongue that helps it', '["hide from owls","catch insects to eat","stay warm in winter","climb up smooth glass"]', 1, 'The sticky tongue grabs insects quickly so the frog can eat them.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A walking stick insect looks just like a twig. This adaptation helps it', '["hide from animals that would eat it","dig in the soil","fly long distances","drink water faster"]', 0, 'Looking like a twig helps the insect blend in and stay safe.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'An owl can turn its head far around to look behind it. This adaptation helps the owl', '["fly faster in storms","stay warm at night","sleep all day","spot prey without moving its body"]', 3, 'Turning its head lets the owl watch for prey quietly without moving.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Why is the wire on an electric cord usually covered in plastic?', '["to make the wire heavier","to cool down the battery","to keep electricity from shocking people","to help the wire glow"]', 2, 'Plastic is an insulator that keeps the electricity safely inside the wire.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'In a flashlight, the energy stored in the batteries changes into', '["water","light energy","sound only","sand"]', 1, 'The flashlight turns the batteries'' stored energy into light.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Which part of a circuit gives the electricity the push to move?', '["the plastic cover","the battery","the empty wire","the bulb"]', 1, 'The battery supplies the energy that pushes electricity through the circuit.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Which object in a circuit changes electrical energy into spinning motion?', '["an electric motor","a paper cup","a plain wire","a rubber band"]', 0, 'An electric motor uses electricity to make parts spin and move.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'A toaster turns electrical energy mostly into', '["light only","sound only","wind","heat energy"]', 3, 'A toaster changes electricity into heat to cook the bread.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'The energy stored in food that your body uses is a kind of', '["wind energy","light energy","sound energy","chemical energy"]', 3, 'Food holds chemical energy that your body uses to move and grow.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'What is the original source of almost all the energy in a food chain on Earth?', '["the soil","the wind","the moon","the sun"]', 3, 'The sun''s energy is captured by plants and then passed along the food chain.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'A solar panel changes energy from the sun into', '["sand","food","wind","electrical energy"]', 3, 'A solar panel turns the sun''s light energy into electrical energy.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'Which of these gives off both light energy and heat energy?', '["a quiet rock","a burning candle","a closed book","a glass of cold water"]', 1, 'A burning candle releases both light and heat energy from its flame.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.energytransfer', NULL, 'A hot cup of cocoa slowly cools down on the table because', '["the cup makes more heat","heat moves from the cocoa to the cooler air","the air pushes heat into the cocoa","the table heats the cocoa"]', 1, 'Heat flows from the warm cocoa into the cooler air around it until it cools.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'When exactly half of the lit side of the moon faces us, we call it a', '["new moon","blue moon","full moon","quarter moon"]', 3, 'A quarter moon is when we see half of the moon''s lit side.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'The moon looks bright at night because it', '["makes its own light","burns like a fire","is full of glowing lava","reflects light from the sun"]', 3, 'The moon has no light of its own; it shines by bouncing back the sun''s light.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'When the moon''s lit shape is more than half but not yet full, it is called a', '["quarter moon","gibbous moon","crescent moon","new moon"]', 1, 'A gibbous moon shows more than half but not all of the lit side.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'Astronauts who walked on the moon bounced easily because the moon has', '["strong winds","less gravity than Earth","deep oceans","more gravity than Earth"]', 1, 'The moon''s gravity is weaker than Earth''s, so things feel much lighter there.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.moon', NULL, 'Footprints left by astronauts on the moon can last a very long time because the moon has', '["many growing plants","heavy daily rainstorms","strong ocean waves","almost no wind or rain to wash them away"]', 3, 'With no wind or rain, nothing wipes the footprints away for a long time.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'A tool that measures how fast the wind is blowing is an', '["ruler","thermometer","anemometer","magnet"]', 2, 'An anemometer measures wind speed by spinning in the wind.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'Big, fluffy white clouds that often appear on fair, sunny days are called', '["rainbows","storm fronts","tornadoes","cumulus clouds"]', 3, 'Cumulus clouds are the puffy white clouds seen on nice days.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'A long period of time with very little or no rain is called a', '["blizzard","drought","flood","hurricane"]', 1, 'A drought is a long stretch of dry weather with little rain.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'Tiny ice crystals or water drops in clouds fall as snow when the air is', '["full of dust","cold enough to freeze the water","completely dry","very warm and sunny"]', 1, 'Snow forms when the air is cold enough for water to freeze into ice crystals.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.weatherclimate', NULL, 'Which two things together best describe the climate of a region?', '["the color of today''s sky","the time the sun set yesterday","the wind speed for one hour","its usual temperature and rainfall over many years"]', 3, 'Climate is described by the long-term pattern of temperature and rainfall.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A duck''s webbed feet are an adaptation that helps it', '["fly higher in the sky","dig deep tunnels","crack open nuts","swim better in water"]', 3, 'Webbed feet act like paddles to push the duck through the water.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A cactus has sharp spines instead of soft leaves. The spines mainly help the cactus by', '["protecting it from animals that would eat it","catching fish for food","making its own light","helping it fly in the wind"]', 0, 'Sharp spines keep hungry animals from eating the cactus.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'Roots that grow very deep underground help a plant', '["make sunlight for itself","scare away animals","reach water far below the surface","move to a new place"]', 2, 'Deep roots let a plant pull up water stored deep in the ground.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'Wide, flat feet help a camel', '["climb tall trees","catch flying birds","swim across the ocean","walk on loose sand without sinking"]', 3, 'Wide feet spread the camel''s weight so it does not sink into the sand.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.adaptations', NULL, 'A flower''s bright colors and sweet smell are adaptations that help it', '["stay cool in summer","attract insects that move its pollen","scare away bees","grow taller than other plants"]', 1, 'Bright colors and smell draw insects that carry pollen from flower to flower.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'If you add a second battery to a simple circuit, the bulb will usually', '["stop working","turn off","change color","shine brighter"]', 3, 'More batteries give more energy, which makes the bulb glow brighter.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Which of these would let electricity flow and complete a circuit?', '["a plastic spoon","a metal paper clip","a wooden block","a rubber eraser"]', 1, 'Metal is a conductor, so the paper clip lets electricity flow through it.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Why should you never put a metal object into an electrical outlet?', '["metal cleans the outlet","metal lets electricity flow and could shock you","metal saves electricity","metal makes the lights brighter"]', 1, 'Metal is a conductor, so electricity could flow into you and cause a dangerous shock.', 10),
  ('science', '4', 2, '4.circuits', NULL, 'Why are electrical wires usually made of metal inside?', '["metal blocks electricity","metal makes no heat ever","metal is a good conductor of electricity","metal is the cheapest plastic"]', 2, 'Metal lets electricity flow through it easily, so it works well inside wires.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'Which mountain range runs along the western United States?', '["Andes Mountains","Alps","Rocky Mountains","Appalachian Mountains"]', 2, 'The Rocky Mountains run through the western U.S.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'The Mississippi River is one of the longest rivers in ___.', '["Australia","Europe","Africa","North America"]', 3, 'The Mississippi is a major North American river.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'The five large lakes between the U.S. and Canada are the ___.', '["Great Lakes","Salt Lakes","Finger Lakes","Clear Lakes"]', 0, 'The Great Lakes are five large lakes on the U.S.–Canada border.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'A region with a hot, sandy climate and little rain is a ___ region.', '["tropical rainforest","wetland","polar","desert"]', 3, 'Deserts are hot or dry regions with little rainfall.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Places near the equator usually have a climate that is ___.', '["warm","freezing","very cold","snowy all year"]', 0, 'Land near the equator gets the most direct sunlight, so it is warm.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'The equator divides the Earth into the Northern and ___ Hemispheres.', '["Eastern","Western","Southern","Central"]', 2, 'The equator splits Earth into Northern and Southern Hemispheres.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'The Prime Meridian divides Earth into the Eastern and ___ Hemispheres.', '["Southern","Northern","Western","Polar"]', 2, 'The Prime Meridian splits Earth into Eastern and Western Hemispheres.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Water, soil, and trees are examples of ___.', '["machines","natural resources","buildings","money"]', 1, 'Natural resources come from nature, like water, soil, and trees.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Florida''s warm, sunny climate is great for growing ___.', '["oranges","snow","ice","cactus forests"]', 0, 'Florida''s warm climate is famous for growing oranges.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'Which mountain range runs along the EASTERN United States?', '["Appalachian Mountains","Andes","Himalayas","Rocky Mountains"]', 0, 'The Appalachian Mountains run along the eastern U.S.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'A region covered in thick trees with lots of rain is a ___.', '["tundra","prairie","forest","desert"]', 2, 'Forests are regions with many trees and plenty of rain.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'A resource that can be replaced naturally, like trees or sunlight, is called ___.', '["renewable","gone forever","frozen","man-made"]', 0, 'Renewable resources can be replaced naturally over time.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'The United States is located in the ___ Hemisphere (north of the equator).', '["Southern","Eastern only","Polar","Northern"]', 3, 'The U.S. is north of the equator, in the Northern Hemisphere.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'Which two hemispheres does the equator create?', '["Upper and Lower","Northern and Southern","Eastern and Western","Inner and Outer"]', 1, 'The equator is the line that splits Earth into the Northern and Southern Hemispheres.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'Lines of latitude measure distance north or south of which line?', '["The equator","The coastline","The Tropic of Cancer only","The Prime Meridian"]', 0, 'Latitude lines run east to west and tell how far north or south you are from the equator.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'The North Pole is found at how many degrees north latitude?', '["0 degrees","180 degrees north","90 degrees north","45 degrees north"]', 2, 'The North Pole is the farthest point north, located at 90 degrees north latitude.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'South America is located mostly in which hemisphere, north or south?', '["Southern Hemisphere","Northern Hemisphere","Eastern Hemisphere only","It is at the South Pole"]', 0, 'Most of South America lies south of the equator, in the Southern Hemisphere.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'The United States as a whole is located in which hemisphere, north or south of the equator?', '["Eastern Hemisphere","Southern Hemisphere","It is on the equator","Northern Hemisphere"]', 3, 'The United States is north of the equator, so it is in the Northern Hemisphere.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Which U.S. region is known for its many lakes, flat farmland, and growing corn and wheat?', '["The Southwest","The Midwest","The Northeast","The West Coast"]', 1, 'The Midwest has flat plains and rich soil, making it a major farming region.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'A region is an area where places share something in common, such as ___.', '["the same house","the same exact mayor","one single river only","climate or landforms"]', 3, 'Regions are grouped by shared features like climate, landforms, or culture.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Texas is a large state located in which region of the United States?', '["New England","The Pacific Northwest","The Northeast","The Southwest"]', 3, 'Texas is part of the Southwest region of the United States.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'A chain of islands stretching south from the tip of Florida is called the Florida ___.', '["Plains","Keys","Dunes","Hills"]', 1, 'The Florida Keys are a line of small islands off the state''s southern tip.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Mountains, plains, and coasts are examples of ___ that can define a region.', '["landforms","holidays","sports teams","languages"]', 0, 'Regions are often grouped by landforms such as mountains, plains, and coasts.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Which of these is a renewable resource that will not run out?', '["Sunlight","Coal","Oil","Natural gas"]', 0, 'Sunlight is renewable because the Sun keeps shining and does not run out.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Solar panels collect energy from the ___.', '["ocean tides","Sun","wind","Moon"]', 1, 'Solar panels capture energy from sunlight to make electricity.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Saving and reusing resources so they last longer is called ___.', '["pollution","mining","melting","conservation"]', 3, 'Conservation means using resources carefully so they last longer.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Which of these is made by people and is NOT a natural resource?', '["Soil","A plastic water bottle","A tree","A river"]', 1, 'A plastic bottle is made by people, while trees, rivers, and soil are natural resources.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Florida''s many sunny beaches help bring in money through which industry?', '["Coal mining","Tourism","Wheat farming","Maple syrup"]', 1, 'Florida''s warm beaches attract tourists, making tourism a major industry.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'Which country shares the southern border of the United States?', '["Spain","Canada","Mexico","Panama"]', 2, 'Mexico lies directly south of the United States along its southern border.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'Which two states are not connected to the other 48 states on the mainland?', '["Florida and Texas","Alaska and Hawaii","Maine and Ohio","Oregon and Nevada"]', 1, 'Alaska and Hawaii are separated from the other 48 connected states.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'Which U.S. state is the largest in land area?', '["Florida","Texas","California","Alaska"]', 3, 'Alaska is the biggest U.S. state by land area.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'In which U.S. state is the deep, rocky Grand Canyon located?', '["Florida","Arizona","Hawaii","New York"]', 1, 'The Grand Canyon, carved by the Colorado River, is located in Arizona.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'Which two hemispheres does the Prime Meridian create?', '["Northern and Southern","Eastern and Western","Top and Bottom","Front and Back"]', 1, 'The Prime Meridian divides Earth into the Eastern and Western Hemispheres.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'Lines of longitude measure distance east or west of which line?', '["The Prime Meridian","The North Pole","The International Date Line only","The equator"]', 0, 'Longitude lines run north to south and measure how far east or west you are from the Prime Meridian.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'Florida is located in which hemisphere when looking east and west of the Prime Meridian?', '["It is on the Prime Meridian","Southern only","Western Hemisphere","Eastern Hemisphere"]', 2, 'Florida lies west of the Prime Meridian, placing it in the Western Hemisphere.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'Places located near 0 degrees latitude usually have what kind of weather?', '["Very dry deserts only","Snowy and cold all year","No sunlight at all","Warm all year"]', 3, 'Land near the equator gets strong, direct sunlight, so it stays warm all year.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'Europe is found in which hemisphere, north or south of the equator?', '["On the equator","Southern Hemisphere","Northern Hemisphere","At the South Pole"]', 2, 'All of Europe lies north of the equator, in the Northern Hemisphere.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Which U.S. region includes the states of California, Oregon, and Washington?', '["The Northeast","The West","The Midwest","The Southeast"]', 1, 'California, Oregon, and Washington are western states along the Pacific coast.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Which region of the United States contains the Rocky Mountains?', '["The West","The Midwest","The Northeast","The Southeast"]', 0, 'The Rocky Mountains run through western states, part of the West region.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Which region of Florida is the most southern and includes the city of Miami?', '["Central Florida","North Florida","The Panhandle","South Florida"]', 3, 'Miami is located in South Florida, the southern part of the state.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'People often divide a country into regions to make it easier to ___.', '["move the oceans","make it warmer","change the weather","study and compare areas"]', 3, 'Regions help people study and compare different parts of a country.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Which large body of water borders many states in the U.S. Southeast region?', '["Lake Superior","The Arctic Ocean","The Pacific Ocean","The Atlantic Ocean"]', 3, 'The Atlantic Ocean borders the eastern edge of the Southeast region.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Which of these is a natural resource people get from the ground for energy?', '["Plastic toys","Paper money","Glass bottles","Oil"]', 3, 'Oil is a natural resource pumped from the ground and used for energy.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Spinning wind turbines use which renewable resource to make electricity?', '["Oil","Plastic","Coal","Wind"]', 3, 'Wind turbines turn moving air into clean, renewable electricity.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Florida''s long coastlines and warm waters make which industry very important?', '["Coal mining","Fishing","Apple orchards","Ski resorts"]', 1, 'Florida''s coasts and warm waters support a large fishing industry.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Florida''s sunny weather makes it a good place to use which type of clean energy?', '["Solar energy","Coal energy","Volcano heat","Whale oil"]', 0, 'Florida''s many sunny days make solar energy a good clean-energy choice.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Coal, oil, and natural gas are all examples of ___ resources.', '["renewable","nonrenewable","living","man-made"]', 1, 'Coal, oil, and natural gas are fossil fuels that cannot be quickly replaced.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'What is the capital city of the United States?', '["Washington, D.C.","Los Angeles","Chicago","New York City"]', 0, 'Washington, D.C. is the capital of the United States.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'Which country shares a long northern border with the United States?', '["Brazil","Mexico","Cuba","Canada"]', 3, 'Canada lies directly north of the United States along its long border.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'How many states are located in the United States?', '["48","50","52","13"]', 1, 'The United States is made up of 50 states.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'Tampa, a large Florida city, sits on a bay that opens into which body of water?', '["Lake Michigan","The Gulf of Mexico","The Atlantic Ocean","The Pacific Ocean"]', 1, 'Tampa sits on Tampa Bay along Florida''s Gulf of Mexico coast.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'Australia is found mostly in which hemisphere, north or south of the equator?', '["It is on the equator only","Northern Hemisphere","It is at the North Pole","Southern Hemisphere"]', 3, 'Australia lies south of the equator, so it is in the Southern Hemisphere.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'What is the latitude of the equator?', '["45 degrees","90 degrees","180 degrees","0 degrees"]', 3, 'The equator is the starting line for latitude, so it is at 0 degrees.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'Which continent is the only one located in all four hemispheres?', '["Australia","Africa","Antarctica","Europe"]', 1, 'Africa is crossed by both the equator and the Prime Meridian, placing parts in all four hemispheres.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'As you travel farther from the equator toward the poles, the weather usually becomes ___.', '["windier only","colder","hotter","wetter every day"]', 1, 'Sunlight hits at a slant near the poles, so the weather grows colder farther from the equator.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'Which hemisphere is Antarctica located in, north or south?', '["Eastern Hemisphere only","Southern Hemisphere","Northern Hemisphere","Western Hemisphere only"]', 1, 'Antarctica surrounds the South Pole, placing it in the Southern Hemisphere.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Which U.S. region is home to states like New York, Massachusetts, and Maine?', '["The Southwest","The West","The Southeast","The Northeast"]', 3, 'New York, Massachusetts, and Maine are all in the Northeast region.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Florida belongs to the Southeast region, which is also known for its warm and ___ climate.', '["humid","frozen","arctic","dry desert"]', 0, 'The Southeast, including Florida, has a warm and humid climate.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'The northwestern part of Florida that is long and narrow is called the ___.', '["Peninsula","Panhandle","Everglades","Keys"]', 1, 'The narrow strip in northwest Florida is known as the Panhandle.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'The New England area, with states like Vermont and New Hampshire, is part of which larger region?', '["The Northeast","The Midwest","The Southeast","The West"]', 0, 'New England states are located within the Northeast region.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Cold, snowy winters are most common in which U.S. region?', '["Hawaii","The Southeast","South Florida","The Northeast"]', 3, 'The Northeast has cold, snowy winters compared to the warm Southeast.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Florida''s warm climate and sandy soil make it a top state for growing which fruit?', '["Apples","Pineapples","Cranberries","Oranges"]', 3, 'Florida is famous for growing oranges in its warm, sunny climate.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Why is fresh water an important natural resource?', '["It cannot be used for farming","People, plants, and animals need it to live","It is only used for swimming","It is never found in rivers"]', 1, 'All living things need fresh water to survive, making it a vital resource.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Rich, fertile soil is an important natural resource because it helps people ___.', '["stop the rain","build roads only","grow crops","make plastic"]', 2, 'Good soil lets farmers grow the crops that feed people and animals.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Phosphate, a mineral mined in Florida, is mostly used to make ___.', '["ice for skating","fertilizer for plants","glass for windows","gasoline for cars"]', 1, 'Florida mines phosphate, which is used to make fertilizer that helps plants grow.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.resources', NULL, 'Why should people use nonrenewable resources carefully?', '["They make more rain","They cannot be replaced quickly once used up","They grow back every night","There is an endless supply"]', 1, 'Nonrenewable resources take a very long time to form, so they must be used wisely.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'Which famous wetland and ''River of Grass'' is found in southern Florida?', '["Yellowstone","The Everglades","The Great Lakes","The Grand Canyon"]', 1, 'The Everglades is a large wetland in southern Florida known as the River of Grass.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'Florida is shaped like a peninsula, which means it has water on ___ sides.', '["zero","three","all four","one"]', 1, 'A peninsula has water on three sides, which describes the shape of Florida.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'Which large national capital area is located between Maryland and Virginia?', '["Atlanta","Boston","Washington, D.C.","Denver"]', 2, 'Washington, D.C. sits along the Potomac River between Maryland and Virginia.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'When it is summer in the Northern Hemisphere, what season is it in the Southern Hemisphere?', '["Winter","Spring everywhere","No seasons there","Summer"]', 0, 'The hemispheres have opposite seasons, so summer in the north means winter in the south.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'What is the longitude of the Prime Meridian?', '["360 degrees","90 degrees","0 degrees","100 degrees"]', 2, 'The Prime Meridian is the starting line for longitude, so it is at 0 degrees.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.hemispheres', NULL, 'Latitude and longitude lines together form a pattern used to find places called a ___.', '["border","scale","grid","legend"]', 2, 'Crossing latitude and longitude lines make a grid that helps locate any place on Earth.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Which U.S. region includes the states of Florida and Georgia?', '["The Southeast","The Midwest","The Northeast","The Pacific Northwest"]', 0, 'Florida and Georgia are part of the Southeast region of the United States.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'The Southwest region of the United States is known for having a lot of ___.', '["glaciers and ice","thick rainforest","frozen tundra","hot, dry desert land"]', 3, 'States like Arizona and New Mexico in the Southwest have hot, dry desert climates.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'The Great Plains are wide, flat lands found mostly in which U.S. region?', '["The Northeast","The Midwest","The Southeast","The Pacific Coast"]', 1, 'The Great Plains stretch across the central Midwest with flat, grassy land.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Central Florida is famous for theme parks near which city?', '["Orlando","Key West","Pensacola","Tallahassee"]', 0, 'Orlando in Central Florida is well known for its theme parks.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.regions', NULL, 'Which U.S. region is most likely to have palm trees and beaches with warm winters?', '["The Northeast","The Midwest","The Pacific Northwest","The Southeast"]', 3, 'The warm Southeast region, including Florida, has palm trees and mild winters.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'Lake Okeechobee, the largest freshwater lake in Florida, is located in which part of the state?', '["The far north Panhandle","South-central Florida","Off the Atlantic coast","In the Florida Keys"]', 1, 'Lake Okeechobee is a very large freshwater lake in south-central Florida.', 10),
  ('geography', '4', 2, 'geo.4.usa', NULL, 'Jacksonville, one of Florida''s largest cities, is located on the coast of which ocean?', '["The Pacific Ocean","The Indian Ocean","The Arctic Ocean","The Atlantic Ocean"]', 3, 'Jacksonville sits on Florida''s northeast Atlantic coast.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'How many original colonies became the first United States?', '["13","20","7","50"]', 0, 'There were 13 original colonies.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'The 13 colonies were located along the ___ coast of North America.', '["Atlantic","Pacific","Arctic","western"]', 0, 'The 13 colonies were along the Atlantic (eastern) coast.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'The Declaration of Independence said the colonies were free from the rule of ___.', '["France","Canada","Spain","Great Britain"]', 3, 'The colonies declared independence from Great Britain in 1776.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'In what year did the United States declare its independence?', '["1900","2000","1776","1492"]', 2, 'The Declaration of Independence was signed in 1776.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'Who is often called the main author of the Declaration of Independence?', '["John Adams","Thomas Jefferson","George Washington","Benjamin Franklin"]', 1, 'Thomas Jefferson was the main writer of the Declaration of Independence.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'Benjamin Franklin was a famous American known as a writer, inventor, and ___.', '["movie star","race car driver","statesman","astronaut"]', 2, 'Franklin was an inventor, writer, and leader (statesman) in early America.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'Florida became the 27th U.S. state in ___.', '["2001","1845","1776","1950"]', 1, 'Florida joined the United States as the 27th state in 1845.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'What is the capital city of Florida?', '["Tampa","Tallahassee","Miami","Orlando"]', 1, 'Tallahassee is the capital of Florida (not its biggest city).', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'People in the 13 colonies were ruled by a king from ___.', '["Mexico","Great Britain","China","Italy"]', 1, 'The colonies were ruled by the British king before independence.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'Is Tallahassee the largest city in Florida?', '["It has no people","No, it is the capital but not the largest","Yes, it is the largest","It is not in Florida"]', 1, 'Tallahassee is the capital; larger cities include Jacksonville and Miami.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'We celebrate the signing of the Declaration of Independence every year on ___.', '["December 25th","January 1st","October 31st","July 4th"]', 3, 'Independence Day is July 4th.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'In a typical colonial New England town, the building where people gathered for worship and town meetings was called the ___.', '["airport","train station","meetinghouse","factory"]', 2, 'The meetinghouse was the center of life in many New England colonial towns.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'Children in colonial times often learned their letters from a paddle-shaped board called a ___.', '["chalkboard map","telephone","laptop","hornbook"]', 3, 'A hornbook was a flat board used to teach colonial children to read.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'In colonial America, candles and lamps that burned oil were used to provide ___.', '["light at night","heat for cars","running water","electricity"]', 0, 'Before electricity, colonists used candles and oil lamps for light.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'The 13 colonies are often grouped into three regions: New England, the Middle Colonies, and the ___ Colonies.', '["Pacific","Northern","Western","Southern"]', 3, 'The three colonial regions were New England, Middle, and Southern.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'In Jamestown, the first lasting English colony, an early important crop that colonists sold was ___.', '["coffee","tobacco","chocolate","bananas"]', 1, 'Tobacco became Jamestown''s most valuable crop to sell.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'Which holiday honors the men and women who serve or have served in the U.S. military, celebrated on November 11?', '["Veterans Day","Labor Day","New Year''s Day","Thanksgiving"]', 0, 'Veterans Day, on November 11, honors all who served in the armed forces.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'Which holiday in late November began as a harvest celebration shared by the Pilgrims and the Wampanoag people?', '["Thanksgiving","Columbus Day","Flag Day","Memorial Day"]', 0, 'Thanksgiving recalls a 1621 harvest feast shared by Pilgrims and the Wampanoag.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'The leader of the Continental Army during the American Revolution was ___.', '["Benjamin Franklin","Thomas Jefferson","George Washington","King George III"]', 2, 'George Washington commanded the Continental Army during the Revolution.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'Which Spanish explorer is known for exploring Florida in 1513 and giving it its name?', '["Henry Hudson","Daniel Boone","George Washington","Ponce de Leon"]', 3, 'Ponce de Leon explored Florida in 1513 and named the land.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'A Native American people closely connected to Florida''s history are the ___.', '["Seminole","Aztecs","Vikings","Pilgrims"]', 0, 'The Seminole are a Native American people closely tied to Florida''s history.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'A large area of wetlands in southern Florida famous for its wildlife is the ___.', '["Great Plains","Sahara Desert","Rocky Mountains","Everglades"]', 3, 'The Everglades is a vast wetland region in southern Florida.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'Many early Florida settlements grew up near the coast because the ocean made it easy to ___.', '["trade and travel by ship","grow corn","build railroads","mine gold"]', 0, 'Coastal towns made trade and travel by ship easier for early settlers.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'The Spanish explorer who founded St. Augustine in 1565 was ___.', '["Pedro Menendez","Paul Revere","Henry Ford","Thomas Jefferson"]', 0, 'Pedro Menendez founded St. Augustine in 1565.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'The war the American colonies fought to win freedom from Great Britain is called the ___.', '["World War I","French Revolution","Civil War","American Revolution"]', 3, 'The American Revolution was fought to gain independence from Britain.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'The American Revolution ended with the colonies winning their ___.', '["king","independence","colonies in Britain","tea"]', 1, 'The colonies won their independence from Britain in the Revolution.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'After winning independence, the new country was named the ___.', '["British Colonies","Kingdom of America","New England","United States of America"]', 3, 'The free colonies formed the United States of America.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'In the Civil War, the Southern states that left the country were known as the ___.', '["Union","Colonies","Allies","Confederacy"]', 3, 'The Southern states formed the Confederacy during the Civil War.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'Most people in the 13 colonies earned a living mainly by ___.', '["building cars","mining gold for the king","farming","flying planes"]', 2, 'Farming was the most common way colonists made a living.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'Many colonial homes were heated and used for cooking by a single ___.', '["microwave","electric oven","fireplace","furnace with a thermostat"]', 2, 'Colonial families cooked and stayed warm using an open fireplace.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'A young person who lived and worked with a craftsman to learn a trade was called an ___.', '["ambassador","apprentice","engineer","explorer"]', 1, 'An apprentice learned a skill by working for a master craftsman.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'Large farms in the Southern Colonies that grew crops like tobacco were called ___.', '["airports","skyscrapers","plantations","factories"]', 2, 'Plantations were large Southern farms that grew cash crops like tobacco.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'Jamestown, founded in 1607, was located in which present-day state?', '["Texas","Florida","Virginia","California"]', 2, 'Jamestown was the first lasting English colony, located in Virginia.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'President Abraham Lincoln is best remembered for helping to end ___ in the United States.', '["baseball","schools","slavery","farming"]', 2, 'Lincoln helped end slavery during and after the Civil War.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'Which civil rights leader gave the famous "I Have a Dream" speech?', '["Martin Luther King Jr.","Henry Ford","George Washington","Paul Revere"]', 0, 'Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. gave the "I Have a Dream" speech in 1963.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'The American flag is sometimes nicknamed the ___.', '["Big Dipper","Red Cross","Stars and Stripes","Golden Gate"]', 2, 'The U.S. flag is nicknamed the Stars and Stripes for its design.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'Memorial Day is a holiday set aside to honor ___.', '["explorers","soldiers who died serving the country","famous inventors","the first colonists"]', 1, 'Memorial Day honors members of the military who died in service.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'Which woman is famous for refusing to give up her bus seat, helping the civil rights movement?', '["Sacagawea","Betsy Ross","Pocahontas","Rosa Parks"]', 3, 'Rosa Parks helped the civil rights movement by refusing to give up her bus seat.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'The name "Florida" comes from Spanish words meaning ___.', '["sunny beach","big swamp","full of flowers","new land"]', 2, 'Florida means "flowery" or "full of flowers" in Spanish.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'Florida is a peninsula, which means it is land that is surrounded by water on ___.', '["one side","three sides","all sides","no sides"]', 1, 'A peninsula is land surrounded by water on three sides.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'Today many rockets and spacecraft are launched from which place in Florida?', '["Kennedy Space Center","Independence Hall","Mount Rushmore","Plymouth Rock"]', 0, 'NASA launches spacecraft from the Kennedy Space Center in Florida.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'A famous Spanish fort built of stone to protect St. Augustine is the ___.', '["Alamo","Liberty Bell","Castillo de San Marcos","Fort Knox"]', 2, 'The Castillo de San Marcos is an old Spanish stone fort in St. Augustine.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'Florida is found in which region of the United States?', '["the Northwest","the far North","the Midwest","the Southeast"]', 3, 'Florida is located in the southeastern United States.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'Colonists were angry about paying taxes to Britain without having a say. This idea was called "no taxation without ___."', '["representation","election","education","money"]', 0, 'Colonists protested taxes passed without their representation in government.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'The very first battles of the American Revolution were fought at Lexington and ___.', '["Concord","Plymouth","Jamestown","Gettysburg"]', 0, 'The Revolution began with battles at Lexington and Concord in 1775.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'The famous saying "Give me liberty, or give me death!" was spoken by ___.', '["Abraham Lincoln","Patrick Henry","George Washington","Paul Revere"]', 1, 'Patrick Henry said "Give me liberty, or give me death!" to urge independence.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'Who was president of the United States during the Civil War?', '["Abraham Lincoln","Thomas Jefferson","George Washington","Theodore Roosevelt"]', 0, 'Abraham Lincoln was president during the Civil War.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'The first ten changes added to the U.S. Constitution that protect people''s freedoms are called the ___.', '["Liberty Bell","Bill of Rights","Boston Tea Party","Mayflower Compact"]', 1, 'The Bill of Rights is the first ten amendments protecting people''s freedoms.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'Which colony was started as a place where Pilgrims could worship freely?', '["Las Vegas","Detroit","Chicago","Plymouth"]', 3, 'The Pilgrims founded Plymouth Colony in 1620 seeking religious freedom.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'A skilled colonial worker such as a blacksmith or shoemaker was known as a ___.', '["astronaut","governor","pilot","craftsman"]', 3, 'Craftsmen made goods like horseshoes and shoes by hand in the colonies.', 10);
insert into public.questions (subject_id, grade, difficulty, skill, standard, prompt, choices, answer_index, explanation, xp) values
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'The colony of Pennsylvania was founded by William Penn, who belonged to a group called the ___.', '["Vikings","Romans","Quakers","Aztecs"]', 2, 'William Penn was a Quaker who founded Pennsylvania.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'To travel and carry goods over land, colonists most often used ___.', '["cars","subway trains","horses and wagons","airplanes"]', 2, 'Colonists relied on horses and wagons because cars did not yet exist.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'Colonial families usually got their water by ___.', '["turning on a faucet","using a garden hose","drawing it from a well","buying bottled water"]', 2, 'Colonists drew water from wells since there was no indoor plumbing.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'On which holiday do Americans honor both George Washington and Abraham Lincoln?', '["April Fools'' Day","Valentine''s Day","Halloween","Presidents'' Day"]', 3, 'Presidents'' Day honors past presidents, including Washington and Lincoln.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'We celebrate Martin Luther King Jr. Day in which month?', '["July","January","December","October"]', 1, 'Martin Luther King Jr. Day is observed in January each year.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'Who made a midnight ride to warn colonists that British soldiers were coming?', '["Henry Ford","Daniel Boone","Paul Revere","Robert E. Lee"]', 2, 'Paul Revere rode to warn colonists the British were coming in 1775.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.figures', NULL, 'The song "The Star-Spangled Banner" is the United States ___.', '["birthday song","Pledge of Allegiance","national anthem","state song"]', 2, '"The Star-Spangled Banner" is the national anthem of the United States.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'Which Florida city, founded in 1565, is the oldest continuously settled city in the United States?', '["Miami","Jacksonville","St. Augustine","Orlando"]', 2, 'St. Augustine, founded in 1565, is the oldest U.S. city.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'The large body of water on the west side of Florida is the ___.', '["Gulf of Mexico","Great Lakes","Pacific Ocean","Mississippi River"]', 0, 'The Gulf of Mexico lies along Florida''s western coast.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'Before becoming a U.S. state, Florida was first a ___ controlled by another country.', '["city","river","territory","kingdom"]', 2, 'Florida was a U.S. territory before becoming a state in 1845.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'Which crop became very important to Florida''s economy and is shown on its license plates?', '["potatoes","apples","oranges","wheat"]', 2, 'Oranges are a major Florida crop and a state symbol.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.florida', NULL, 'Early Spanish explorers came to Florida partly hoping to find ___.', '["railroads","oil","gold and riches","electricity"]', 2, 'Spanish explorers searched the Americas hoping to find gold and riches.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'In the Boston Tea Party, angry colonists dumped British ___ into the harbor.', '["books","tea","gold","coal"]', 1, 'Colonists threw British tea into Boston Harbor to protest taxes.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'Which king of Great Britain ruled when the colonies declared independence?', '["King George III","King Henry VIII","King Arthur","King Louis"]', 0, 'King George III ruled Britain when the colonies declared independence.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'The war fought between the Northern and Southern states from 1861 to 1865 was the ___.', '["Revolutionary War","Civil War","War of 1812","World War II"]', 1, 'The Civil War was fought between Northern and Southern states.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'Moving across the country to settle new land in the West was called ___.', '["the Civil War","westward expansion","the Boston Tea Party","the Industrial Age"]', 1, 'Westward expansion was the movement of settlers into the West.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.independence', NULL, 'The set of rules that became the highest law of the United States is the ___.', '["newspaper","city map","king''s decree","Constitution"]', 3, 'The Constitution is the highest law of the United States.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'The Pilgrims sailed to North America in 1620 on a ship named the ___.', '["Queen Mary","Mayflower","Titanic","Santa Maria"]', 1, 'The Pilgrims crossed the Atlantic Ocean on the Mayflower.', 10),
  ('history', '4', 2, 'hist.4.colonies', NULL, 'The 13 colonies belonged to which country before the United States was formed?', '["Great Britain","Canada","Japan","Mexico"]', 0, 'The 13 colonies were ruled by Great Britain before independence.', 10),
