  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'A person who starts and runs their own business is called an ___.', '["customer","entrepreneur","inspector","employee"]', 1, 'An entrepreneur starts and runs a business, taking the risk to earn a profit.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'A business that spends MORE money than it earns is said to take a ___.', '["loss","profit","sale","raise"]', 0, 'A loss happens when costs are greater than the money earned.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'If a business wants to EARN more profit, one way is to lower its ___.', '["quality on purpose","honesty","customers","costs"]', 3, 'Lowering costs while keeping sales the same can raise profit.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'A bakery sells 20 muffins at $2 each. How much money does it take in?', '["$20","$10","$22","$40"]', 3, '20 muffins times $2 each equals $40.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'The skills and effort workers bring to a business are called ___.', '["human resources","money","natural resources","machines"]', 0, 'Human resources are the people and their skills who do the work.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'Opportunity cost is the value of the next-best thing you give up when you make a ___.', '["deposit","profit","choice","tax"]', 2, 'Opportunity cost is what you give up when you choose one thing over another.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'Opportunity cost can be about time, too. Studying instead of playing means your opportunity cost is ___.', '["the play time you gave up","more homework only","extra money earned","a bigger budget"]', 0, 'Choosing to study gives up play time, which is the opportunity cost.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'A town has money for ONE project: a park OR a pool. If it builds the park, the pool is the ___.', '["profit","tax refund","income","opportunity cost"]', 3, 'Choosing the park means giving up the pool, the opportunity cost.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'When a country uses its workers to make cars, the opportunity cost is the OTHER ___ those workers could have made.', '["money","rivers","goods","taxes"]', 2, 'Workers making cars cannot also make other goods, the opportunity cost.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'A baker has only enough flour for bread OR cake. Making bread means the cake is the ___.', '["supply","income","profit","opportunity cost"]', 3, 'Using the flour for bread means giving up the cake, the opportunity cost.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'A school can hire one new teacher OR buy new computers with the same money. Picking the teacher makes the computers the ___.', '["income","opportunity cost","tax","profit"]', 1, 'Choosing the teacher means giving up the computers, the opportunity cost.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.supplydemand', NULL, 'Supply is how much of a good is ___ for people to buy.', '["broken","hidden","free","available"]', 3, 'Supply is the amount of a good available to buy.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.supplydemand', NULL, 'A bad season ruins most of the orange crop, so there are very few oranges. This is low ___.', '["supply","profit","tax","demand"]', 0, 'A small crop means few oranges available, which is low supply.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.supplydemand', NULL, 'When a new phone everyone wants first comes out, the high demand can make the price ___.', '["free","zero","hidden","high"]', 3, 'Strong demand for a new item can keep its price high.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.supplydemand', NULL, 'Which situation would most likely make a price go DOWN?', '["Many items left and few buyers","Everyone wants it badly","Few items left and many buyers","The item is sold out"]', 0, 'High supply and low demand together push prices down.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'Maria earns $20 mowing lawns and spends $12 on a book. How much money does she have left?', '["$32","$12","$8","$20"]', 2, '$20 minus $12 spent leaves $8.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'Sam wants a $30 game. He saves $5 each week. How many weeks until he has enough?', '["10 weeks","3 weeks","6 weeks","5 weeks"]', 2, '$30 divided by $5 each week equals 6 weeks.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'Jen has $15. She wants a $9 shirt and a $8 hat. What does her budget tell her?', '["She has money left over after both","She can buy both easily","She cannot buy both","Both cost the same"]', 2, '$9 plus $8 is $17, which is more than her $15.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'Why is it smart to plan a budget BEFORE going shopping?', '["So things cost more","So the store closes early","So you do not spend more than you have","So you forget the prices"]', 2, 'A budget made ahead of time helps you avoid overspending.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'If a family loses some of its income, the smart budget choice is usually to ___.', '["buy more wants","throw away the budget","spend less on wants","stop buying food"]', 2, 'With less income, families cut back on wants to cover needs.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'The money a business has left AFTER paying all its costs is called ___.', '["profit","demand","scarcity","income tax"]', 0, 'Profit is the money a business keeps after paying its costs.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'A person who works for a business and is paid wages is called an ___.', '["investor","entrepreneur","employee","owner"]', 2, 'An employee works for a business and earns wages or a salary.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'Money a person puts into a business hoping it will grow is called an ___.', '["expense","investment","refund","tax"]', 1, 'An investment is money put into a business to help it grow and earn more.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'Advertising helps a business by telling people about its goods so they will ___.', '["hide them","buy them","ignore them","tax them"]', 1, 'Advertising tells customers about products so they will buy them.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'You spend your only $5 on a snack instead of a sticker pack. The sticker pack is your ___.', '["opportunity cost","profit","income","savings"]', 0, 'The sticker pack is the next-best choice you gave up, the opportunity cost.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'A farmer has one field. Planting corn means the opportunity cost is the ___ she could have grown.', '["tractor","other crop","rain","barn"]', 1, 'Using the field for corn means giving up another crop she could grow.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'To make a good choice, you should compare the benefits of each option with its ___.', '["name","opportunity cost","color","size only"]', 1, 'Comparing benefits to opportunity cost helps you make a good choice.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'Opportunity cost helps explain why you cannot have ___.', '["everything you want at once","any money","any free time","any choices"]', 0, 'Limited resources mean choosing some things means giving up others.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'A good decision-maker thinks about opportunity cost so the choice gives the MOST ___.', '["noise","waiting","homework","benefit"]', 3, 'Weighing opportunity cost helps pick the choice with the most benefit.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.supplydemand', NULL, 'On a very hot day, lots of people want cold water bottles. This is high ___.', '["cost","demand","tax","supply"]', 1, 'Many people wanting water means high demand.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.supplydemand', NULL, 'Which best describes a market?', '["A place where buyers and sellers trade goods and services","A school for teachers","A building with no people","A place to store only money"]', 0, 'A market is where buyers and sellers come together to trade.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.supplydemand', NULL, 'If sellers can make MORE of a product easily, the supply will ___.', '["vanish","shrink","increase","freeze"]', 2, 'Making more of a product increases its supply.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.supplydemand', NULL, 'A store raises the price of a hot new sticker because demand is high. The store hopes to earn more ___.', '["homework","profit","rain","tax"]', 1, 'Raising the price when demand is high can earn the store more profit.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'Money that comes IN to your budget, such as an allowance or pay from a job, is called your ___.', '["tax","debt","expense","income"]', 3, 'Income is the money you receive, such as wages or an allowance.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'In a budget, the part you set aside for the future instead of spending is your ___.', '["savings","income","expenses","bills"]', 0, 'Savings is the money you keep for the future instead of spending now.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'A family''s monthly budget should include money for rent, food, and ___.', '["borrowed toys","other bills like electricity","free gifts","winning the lottery"]', 1, 'Regular bills such as electricity are expenses families plan for.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'A class wants to raise $100 for a trip. They have raised $60. How much more do they need?', '["$160","$40","$100","$60"]', 1, '$100 minus $60 already raised equals $40 still needed.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'An emergency fund is money you save in your budget to use for ___.', '["showing your friends","paying no bills","buying candy daily","surprise costs you did not expect"]', 3, 'An emergency fund covers unexpected costs like a sudden repair.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'A lemonade stand spends $4 on supplies and sells $10 of lemonade. What is the profit?', '["$4","$10","$6","$14"]', 2, 'Profit is $10 earned minus $4 spent, which equals $6.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'When starting a business, an entrepreneur takes a ___ because the business might not succeed.', '["risk","tax","vacation","vote"]', 0, 'Starting a business is a risk because it could lose money.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'Two ice cream shops on the same street trying to get the same customers are in ___.', '["vacation","savings","competition","agreement"]', 2, 'Competition is when businesses try to win the same customers.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'A business that gives good service so people return is building ___.', '["more taxes","loyal customers","higher costs","less income"]', 1, 'Good service brings back loyal customers who buy again.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'Materials from nature, like wood and water, that a business uses are called ___.', '["human resources","profits","natural resources","wages"]', 2, 'Natural resources are materials from nature used to make goods.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'Why does every choice have an opportunity cost?', '["Because money never runs out","Because we cannot have everything, so choosing one means giving up another","Because choices never matter","Because everything is free"]', 1, 'Limited resources mean choosing one thing means giving up another.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'People must weigh opportunity costs because resources like money and time are ___.', '["unimportant","free","endless","limited"]', 3, 'Resources are limited, so people must weigh what they give up.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'Lia buys a $12 book instead of saving the $12. What did she give up by buying the book?', '["The store itself","The chance to save $12","Twelve more books","Her whole allowance forever"]', 1, 'Spending the $12 means giving up the chance to save it.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'When you save money instead of spending it, the opportunity cost is the ___ you did not buy.', '["interest","things","savings","bank"]', 1, 'Saving means giving up the things you could have bought, the opportunity cost.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.supplydemand', NULL, 'When MANY people want a toy but there are only a FEW left, the price usually goes ___.', '["up","to zero","down","away"]', 0, 'High demand and low supply usually push prices up.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.supplydemand', NULL, 'If the price of a popular game drops a lot, more people will likely ___ it.', '["throw away","buy","return","tax"]', 1, 'Lower prices usually make people want to buy more, raising demand.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.supplydemand', NULL, 'In a market, the price is usually set by both supply and ___.', '["weather","homework","demand","color"]', 2, 'Prices in a market are shaped by supply and demand together.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.supplydemand', NULL, 'Strawberries are cheaper in summer because there are LOTS of them. This is high ___.', '["demand","supply","tax","debt"]', 1, 'Plenty of strawberries means high supply, which lowers the price.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.supplydemand', NULL, 'Buyers usually want to buy MORE when the price is ___.', '["low","high","hidden","doubled"]', 0, 'Lower prices usually make buyers want to buy more.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'Money that goes OUT of your budget when you buy things is called an ___.', '["income","interest","savings","expense"]', 3, 'An expense is money you spend on goods and services.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'When you keep track of what you earn and what you spend, you are ___ your money.', '["managing","wasting","losing","ignoring"]', 0, 'Managing money means planning and tracking your income and expenses.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'If you spend LESS than you earn, you are able to ___.', '["lose your income","owe more money","raise the price","save the extra money"]', 3, 'Spending less than you earn leaves extra money you can save.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'Putting your money into groups like ''save,'' ''spend,'' and ''give'' is one way to ___ a budget.', '["lose","spend","organize","hide"]', 2, 'Sorting money into groups helps you organize a budget.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.budget', NULL, 'Anna has $50 budgeted: $30 for food and $10 for a gift. How much is left for saving?', '["$40","$10","$20","$30"]', 1, '$50 minus $30 and $10 leaves $10 to save.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'The things a business must pay for, like supplies and workers, are its ___.', '["savings","taxes","costs","profits"]', 2, 'Costs are what a business pays to make and sell its goods or services.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'A factory that makes goods to sell is acting as a ___.', '["shopper","producer","consumer","taxpayer"]', 1, 'A producer makes goods or provides services to sell.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'Competition between businesses often gives customers lower prices and ___.', '["better choices","closed stores","fewer goods","higher taxes"]', 0, 'Competition pushes businesses to offer better prices and more choices.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'If costs are $30 and the business earns $30, the profit is ___.', '["$60","$0","$30","$15"]', 1, 'When earnings equal costs, there is no profit, so profit is $0.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.business', NULL, 'A car wash washes 15 cars and charges $5 each. Supplies cost $25. What is the profit?', '["$15","$50","$75","$25"]', 1, '15 cars times $5 is $75, minus $25 in costs leaves $50 profit.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'Dana can either go to a movie OR a ballgame on Saturday, but not both. Picking the movie means her opportunity cost is the ___.', '["movie","popcorn","ticket price","ballgame"]', 3, 'Choosing the movie means she gives up the ballgame, her opportunity cost.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'Ben uses his afternoon to read. The opportunity cost is the other things he could have done with that ___.', '["book","time","library","money"]', 1, 'Time is the resource he used, so the cost is the other uses of that time.', 10),
  ('economics', '4', 2, 'econ.4.opportunitycost', NULL, 'Which sentence best shows opportunity cost?', '["I bought a red bike","I chose the red bike, so I gave up the blue bike","Bikes are fun to ride","The store sells many bikes"]', 1, 'Choosing the red bike and giving up the blue one shows opportunity cost.', 10),
